in the world already. Good morning.

459
00:41:30,822 --> 00:41:32,745
That meant "good-bye."

460
00:41:36,411 --> 00:41:38,004
I have work.

461
00:41:42,291 --> 00:41:45,215
Sorry.
I have a lot of work myself.

462
00:41:49,841 --> 00:41:51,684
Good morning.

463
00:41:57,640 --> 00:42:00,359
I really swept her
off her feet.

464
00:42:19,662 --> 00:42:23,132
All right, Foster. Let's do it!

465
00:42:27,754 --> 00:42:31,429
Hello. This is
Carlton Whitfield, 4319.

466
00:42:31,966 --> 00:42:35,345
That's right. I'm still waiting for
that secretary I requested last week.

467
00:42:37,722 --> 00:42:40,020
I realize you're
busy down there...

468
00:42:40,099 --> 00:42:42,568
but I'm typing my own letters
and answering my own calls...

469
00:42:42,643 --> 00:42:44,645
and it's getting to be a pain.

470
00:42:45,521 --> 00:42:46,989
Empty?

471
00:42:47,690 --> 00:42:51,490
Well, I've been here a week,
got my name on the door...

472
00:42:51,611 --> 00:42:54,330
got a desk full of supplies and
a geranium on my window ledge.

473
00:42:54,405 --> 00:42:56,749
What I don't have
is a secretary.

474
00:42:58,284 --> 00:43:00,252
Okay, I'll tell you what.

475
00:43:00,328 --> 00:43:03,798
I'll have Personnel send a boy up from
the mailroom with the requisitions.

476
00:43:03,915 --> 00:43:07,795
Just send me my secretary, okay?
Thank you very much.

477
00:43:23,267 --> 00:43:27,818
Got a memo here. Big cheese in 4319
wants his new secretary pronto.

478
00:43:27,897 --> 00:43:29,899
I got a memo here that's
burning up my fingers.

479
00:43:29,982 --> 00:43:34,533
New suit in 4319 wants his personalized
memos and stationery immediately.

480
00:43:34,534 --> 00:43:36,452
- This guy is hot.
- Who?

481
00:43:36,572 --> 00:43:38,495
I don't know.
Name's on the memo.

482
00:43:38,574 --> 00:43:42,124
He wants nameplates for his <i>door,</i>
and he wants it by noon. Okay?

483
00:43:42,203 --> 00:43:43,625
Smile.

484
00:43:47,917 --> 00:43:51,012
- You're late.
- I already done my rounds.

485
00:43:51,087 --> 00:43:52,760
You didn't punch in.

486
00:43:52,839 --> 00:43:56,719
Well, I couldn't wait to get to it.
Boy, I love my work.

487
00:43:56,843 --> 00:44:00,643
Punch in, then run this up to Personnel
and wait for an answer.

488
00:44:00,721 --> 00:44:02,268
Right.

489
00:44:23,035 --> 00:44:25,788
I'm Jean, your secretary.

490
00:44:25,872 --> 00:44:27,795
I'm not wearing anything.

491
00:44:27,874 --> 00:44:30,343
I see that.

492
00:44:30,751 --> 00:44:32,753
It was warm.

493
00:44:33,796 --> 00:44:36,675
Seems cooler now.
I'll get dressed.

494
00:44:37,925 --> 00:44:41,270
Yes, sir.
I'll move my stuff in.

495
00:44:41,429 --> 00:44:43,807
<i>Great, Jean. Good idea.</i>

496
00:44:57,612 --> 00:44:59,580
Jean? I have some notes here.

497
00:44:59,655 --> 00:45:02,579
I also have some charts,
some graphs, some tapes.

498
00:45:02,658 --> 00:45:05,161
They're all sorted by department.
Can you read my handwriting?

499
00:45:05,244 --> 00:45:06,996
- Sort of.
- Do your best.

500
00:45:07,121 --> 00:45:09,874
I need some poster boards,
coloured pencils, coloured push pins...

501
00:45:09,957 --> 00:45:14,554
T square, drawing table, lots of
pencils, and my lunch. Chinese?

502
00:45:17,882 --> 00:45:20,305
- Hey, 4319?
- Yeah.

503
00:45:24,597 --> 00:45:26,144
Great.

504
00:45:27,350 --> 00:45:29,648
- Morning.
- Morning.

505
00:45:35,274 --> 00:45:37,868
- Morning.
- Hi.

506
00:46:57,606 --> 00:47:00,405
Hello again. Small world.

507
00:47:01,569 --> 00:47:03,412
Hello.

508
00:47:11,120 --> 00:47:13,498
Are you standing still
for some purpose?

509
00:47:14,832 --> 00:47:16,960
Hey, I'm just soaking up
the atmosphere.

510
00:47:19,295 --> 00:47:21,468
Executive lounge, huh?

511
00:47:21,547 --> 00:47:24,763
- Care to do a little lounging?
- No, I'm busy.

512
00:47:24,764 --> 00:47:27,979
Ron, did you get those figures
on transfer costs and insurance?

513
00:47:28,054 --> 00:47:31,024
Not yet. Big delay in Chicago.

514
00:47:31,098 --> 00:47:34,227
- Damn! I really need them!
- Blame Chicago.

515
00:47:34,310 --> 00:47:36,312
- Maybe I can help.
- I'm sorry?

516
00:47:36,395 --> 00:47:38,193
Transfer costs
and insurance for what?

517
00:47:38,272 --> 00:47:40,991
By the time I explained,
I could find out myself.

518
00:47:41,484 --> 00:47:43,486
Ron. Big weenie.

519
00:47:43,569 --> 00:47:46,368
Hey, listen. Why don't you
explain it to me over lunch?

520
00:47:46,447 --> 00:47:49,826
- I'll have the answer by dessert.
- I don't eat lunch.

521
00:47:51,118 --> 00:47:53,667
Why don't we start this again?
Carlton Whitfield. And you're?

522
00:47:53,788 --> 00:47:55,790
Annoyed. Shit.

523
00:47:57,083 --> 00:48:00,460
You know, I'm just
trying to be friendly.

524
00:48:00,461 --> 00:48:03,806
You picked a bad time. I was counting
on those figures from Ron.

525
00:48:03,923 --> 00:48:05,971
- Christy Wills. How do you do?
- Good.

526
00:48:06,634 --> 00:48:09,433
Terrible news. Just awful!

527
00:48:09,970 --> 00:48:12,223
Conference room, everybody.
Come on. On the double.

528
00:48:15,810 --> 00:48:18,063
- You don't eat lunch. Do you eat dinner?
- Occasionally.

529
00:48:18,145 --> 00:48:19,772
- Tonight?
- Booked.

530
00:48:19,855 --> 00:48:22,233
- Tomorrow night?
- Booked.

531
00:48:22,316 --> 00:48:25,195
All right, but don't beg, okay?
It's embarrassing.

532
00:48:30,825 --> 00:48:32,293
Who are you?

533
00:48:34,870 --> 00:48:37,373
Carlton Whitfield.
New employee.

534
00:48:40,418 --> 00:48:42,887
I didn't get a memo on that.

535
00:48:43,003 --> 00:48:44,596
You will.

536
00:48:44,672 --> 00:48:48,222
All right.
As long <i>as</i> I get the memo.

537
00:48:52,430 --> 00:48:56,560
The absolute worst has happened.
We are the target of a corporate raid.

538
00:48:56,642 --> 00:49:00,647
Donald Davenport has filed a 13-D.

539
00:49:00,729 --> 00:49:02,697
A 13-D?

540
00:49:02,773 --> 00:49:04,775
He's acquired five percent
of the stock...

541
00:49:04,859 --> 00:49:09,660
and this is definitely the beginning of
a hostile takeover of our corporation.

542
00:49:09,738 --> 00:49:12,867
I think we all know what happened the
last time Davenport took over a company.

543
00:49:12,950 --> 00:49:14,543
Everyone was canned!

544
00:49:15,703 --> 00:49:18,877
Mr Prescott has sent down word
of what he <i>wants</i> us to do.

545
00:49:18,956 --> 00:49:22,586
We are to recommend cuts
in every department.

546
00:49:22,710 --> 00:49:27,762
Our job is to slash the red ink
in every nook and cranny...

547
00:49:27,840 --> 00:49:31,765
because our company needs
the cash for its defence.

548
00:49:33,721 --> 00:49:36,019
Anybody wanna fire
the first shot?

549
00:49:37,558 --> 00:49:39,060
Kill Toledo.

550
00:49:42,146 --> 00:49:44,194
If we close down
our distribution centres...

551
00:49:44,273 --> 00:49:46,071
in Toledo, Joplin, Jacksonville...

552
00:49:46,192 --> 00:49:48,570
we'll slash the red ink
completely off the books.

553
00:49:51,614 --> 00:49:54,037
Whitfield, you don't have
to raise your hand. Just speak.

554
00:49:54,116 --> 00:49:55,834
Thank you.

555
00:49:55,910 --> 00:49:59,412
Well, I know I'm new here
and everything.

556
00:49:59,413 --> 00:50:01,586
On the surface, these cuts
seem like a good idea...

557
00:50:01,665 --> 00:50:03,338
"Seem like a good idea"?

558
00:50:03,459 --> 00:50:05,928
But closing down those distribution
centres would be a big mistake.

559
00:50:06,003 --> 00:50:09,507
It <i>so</i> happens that those closings
are exactly what Mr Prescott wants.

560
00:50:10,424 --> 00:50:12,927
Well, then Mr Prescott hasn't
thought things through very well.

561
00:50:13,844 --> 00:50:16,597
I'm going to tell him you said that.

562
00:50:17,097 --> 00:50:19,270
Good. Closing down
those centres...

563
00:50:19,350 --> 00:50:21,648
will put a strain on
this company's cash position.

564
00:50:21,727 --> 00:50:24,901
In the long run, those cuts are going
to hurt this company's innate value.

565
00:50:24,902 --> 00:50:28,322
Innate value?
What is he talking about?

566
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:31,199
Davidson here will back me up
on this. Davidson?

567
00:50:31,278 --> 00:50:32,871
I'm Proctor. He's Davidson.

568
00:50:32,988 --> 00:50:34,990
Well, damn it,
Davidson, tell him!

569
00:50:35,074 --> 00:50:37,793
You wrote a memo to Mr Thomas
explaining what I'm talking about.

570
00:50:37,868 --> 00:50:40,246
Well, how did you know
I wrote that memo?

571
00:50:46,001 --> 00:50:48,003
How did I know
you wrote that memo?

572
00:50:51,090 --> 00:50:54,560
Who else could write
that memo, Davidson?

573
00:50:55,386 --> 00:50:57,980
That memo was famous.

574
00:50:58,055 --> 00:51:00,057
That memo was a masterpiece.

575
00:51:00,140 --> 00:51:04,020
Clear, concise, to the point.
That was the best damn memo I ever read!

576
00:51:04,478 --> 00:51:07,857
In fact, that memo wasn't even a memo.
That memo was literature.

577
00:51:07,858 --> 00:51:09,654
- Well, thank you.
- You're welcome.

578
00:51:09,733 --> 00:51:13,237
If you have finished your book report,
could you explain what your point is?

579
00:51:13,362 --> 00:51:16,832
- The point is, we gotta be bold.
- That's my point.

580
00:51:16,907 --> 00:51:19,831
We gotta build. We gotta expand.

581
00:51:19,910 --> 00:51:22,709
Expanding is the only way
to help the situation.

582
00:51:22,830 --> 00:51:24,798
We gotta make
this company so damn strong...

583
00:51:24,873 --> 00:51:28,218
Davenport won't be able to find anyone
willing to give up Pemrose stock.

584
00:51:28,294 --> 00:51:31,468
It'll be too damn valuable.
Then we'll buy his ass out!

585
00:51:37,303 --> 00:51:39,806
- How old are you, Mister...
- Whitfield.

586
00:51:39,972 --> 00:51:41,974
- Yes.
- Twenty-four.

587
00:51:42,057 --> 00:51:44,606
I think you should keep quiet
until you're at least 25.

588
00:51:45,561 --> 00:51:49,191
If I may, I don't think Whitfield's age
should be an issue here.

589
00:51:49,315 --> 00:51:52,319
No one is interested
in your opinion, Davis.

590
00:51:52,401 --> 00:51:54,779
We gotta block that takeover.

591
00:51:54,862 --> 00:51:56,864
I'm too old to look
for another job.

592
00:51:56,947 --> 00:51:59,075
Nobody in their right mind
would hire me.

593
00:52:02,745 --> 00:52:06,591
This meeting is going nowhere!

594
00:52:06,707 --> 00:52:09,256
Mr Prescott's command stands!

595
00:52:09,335 --> 00:52:12,555
We are to find those cuts!

596
00:52:12,630 --> 00:52:14,473
Meeting adjourned.

597
00:52:19,678 --> 00:52:22,477
You'll pick up the coats.
That looks like one only a lot smaller.

598
00:52:22,556 --> 00:52:25,150
Hey! Harvard!
Where the hell've you been?

599
00:52:25,225 --> 00:52:29,526
Personnel. You said to wait for
an answer. They are real slow up there.

600
00:52:30,731 --> 00:52:33,280
There's something going on
around here, Foster.

601
00:52:33,359 --> 00:52:36,784
I'm gonna be on you like a rash.
You got that? Like a rash.

602
00:52:36,904 --> 00:52:40,124
Won't the other guys get jealous?
Heads!

603
00:54:09,913 --> 00:54:11,915
You guys were good tonight.

604
00:54:23,510 --> 00:54:27,185
Oh, God.
What are you doin' here?

605
00:54:27,264 --> 00:54:30,564
Brantley, darling, I heard you calling
me telepathically... I'm very psychic...

606
00:54:30,642 --> 00:54:32,736
<i>so</i> of course
I rushed right over.

607
00:54:34,313 --> 00:54:38,534
- I would've used the phone.
- Mental telepathy's much more reliable.

608
00:54:40,194 --> 00:54:42,242
Aren't you gonna ask me in?

609
00:54:44,907 --> 00:54:47,501
Yeah. Sorry.

610
00:54:47,576 --> 00:54:49,328
Just a minute.

611
00:54:59,922 --> 00:55:02,425
Father used to live like this
before he founded Pemrose.

612
00:55:02,591 --> 00:55:04,343
Aunt Vera...

613
00:55:04,426 --> 00:55:07,726
I had a hell of a day,
and I really have to get some sleep.

614
00:55:08,931 --> 00:55:11,480
Brantley, you're a young man.

615
00:55:12,643 --> 00:55:15,112
Young men have lots of energy.

616
00:55:18,232 --> 00:55:19,404
<i>Look.</i>

617
00:55:21,360 --> 00:55:24,034
- We have a problem.
- What?

618
00:55:25,364 --> 00:55:28,368
Your husband is my boss.

619
00:55:28,450 --> 00:55:31,624
Oh, him. We won't tell him.

620
00:55:32,663 --> 00:55:35,337
Besides,
Howard's working late tonight.

621
00:55:35,457 --> 00:55:38,131
On <i>whom,</i> I have no idea.

622
00:55:39,586 --> 00:55:42,760
You look very beautiful
tonight, Christy.

623
00:55:42,840 --> 00:55:46,515
Thank you. <i>Now,</i> there are some
business things we should discuss.

624
00:55:46,635 --> 00:55:50,139
Do you think that this restaurant
has an upstairs with beds in it?

625
00:55:50,222 --> 00:55:52,645
Howard, please!

626
00:55:52,724 --> 00:55:56,194
I don't feel altogether good
about what's happened between us.

627
00:55:56,895 --> 00:55:59,193
You are married.

628
00:55:59,273 --> 00:56:01,992
- I'm not married.
- You are married!

629
00:56:02,067 --> 00:56:06,117
Well, yeah, I am married,
but she and I have an understanding.

630
00:56:26,383 --> 00:56:29,011
- I love you.
- I don't really think so.

631
00:56:29,177 --> 00:56:32,522
Well, then I lust after you.
That oughta be worth something.

632
00:56:32,598 --> 00:56:34,976
To you, perhaps.
Now, let's talk business.

633
00:56:35,058 --> 00:56:37,481
I pitched the need for cutbacks
at the meeting today...

634
00:56:37,561 --> 00:56:40,777
but a dissenting opinion <i>was</i> offered
by Carlton Whitfield.

635
00:56:40,778 --> 00:56:43,571
Who's Carlton Whitfield?
I didn't hire any Carlton Whitfield.

636
00:56:43,692 --> 00:56:45,239
Somebody did.

637
00:56:45,319 --> 00:56:48,493
- Oh, my God. Donald Davenport.
- What?

638
00:56:48,572 --> 00:56:51,701
He may be a plant for Davenport,
gathering information on the takeover.

639
00:56:51,783 --> 00:56:55,583
It's just like him. I want you
to get close to this guy Whitfield.

640
00:56:55,662 --> 00:56:57,380
Find out what he's up to.

641
00:56:57,456 --> 00:57:00,630
- You want me to spy on him?
- No, I don't want you to spy on him.

642
00:57:00,709 --> 00:57:02,677
I want you to get
to be friends with him...

643
00:57:02,753 --> 00:57:04,755
then rifle through his papers
and tell me what you find.

644
00:57:04,838 --> 00:57:06,715
That's spying, Howard.

645
00:57:06,798 --> 00:57:09,847
<i>Look,</i> you have got to drop
this incessant innocence.

646
00:57:09,927 --> 00:57:13,898
Life is harsh and ugly,
and only the strong survive.

647
00:57:13,972 --> 00:57:16,066
Or didn't they teach you that
at Harvard?

648
00:57:20,103 --> 00:57:22,652
- What you got in there?
- My lunch.

649
00:57:22,731 --> 00:57:24,825
Your lunch? In a briefcase?

650
00:57:24,900 --> 00:57:27,653
Yeah. Ran out of brown bags.

651
00:57:29,029 --> 00:57:31,282
One of you guys got
a spare pair of laces?

652
00:57:31,365 --> 00:57:33,788
Hey, man, I had a babe last night
you wouldn't believe.

653
00:57:33,867 --> 00:57:38,418
"Ta-Na's" out to here, man.
She was fine. Where'd he go?

654
00:57:55,931 --> 00:57:58,730
- Coming through. Excuse me.
- Take it easy. Come on.

655
00:57:58,809 --> 00:58:00,982
Sorry.

656
00:58:32,467 --> 00:58:34,219
- What a nightmare.
- Stuck again?

657
00:58:34,302 --> 00:58:36,430
- I'm all right, though. I'm fine.
- You okay?

658
00:58:36,513 --> 00:58:40,563
- You all right?
- Don't worry about me. Thanks.

659
00:58:40,642 --> 00:58:44,943
<i>Jean,</i> transcribe these notes. There's
some things on there I need right away.

660
00:58:45,564 --> 00:58:48,568
Make copies of this,
copies of this.

661
00:58:48,650 --> 00:58:51,028
- Did you get those supplies I needed?
- Yes, sir.

662
00:58:51,111 --> 00:58:54,206
Good. I'll be back later.

663
00:58:59,870 --> 00:59:01,872
- Gentlemen.
- Good morning.

664
00:59:10,464 --> 00:59:13,308
- Goddam that thing!
- This thing stuck again?

665
00:59:16,636 --> 00:59:18,513
These elevators are stuck again?

666
00:59:21,058 --> 00:59:24,358
I'm sick and tired of these
elevators always gettin' stuck.

667
00:59:32,069 --> 00:59:35,414
Hi, Jean. Will you take
those to the cleaners?

668
00:59:58,470 --> 01:00:01,269
These are <i>some</i> of the notes
I found in Whitfield's office.

669
01:00:01,348 --> 01:00:04,397
If you want anything more,
you can go after it yourself.

670
01:00:04,643 --> 01:00:06,771
Do you think he's working
for Davenport?

671
01:00:06,853 --> 01:00:11,029
I have no idea.
I'm out of the spy business.

672
01:00:15,987 --> 01:00:18,866
We can't wait for Whitfield
any longer. Let's get started.

673
01:00:19,491 --> 01:00:23,246
Davis here has prepared what I'm sure
is a thoroughly incompetent analysis...

674
01:00:23,247 --> 01:00:25,748
but let's listen to him read it
before we start criticizing.

675
01:00:25,831 --> 01:00:27,799
Fine. I won't read it at all.
Is that all right?

676
01:00:27,874 --> 01:00:30,923
You have a bad attitude, and I am
gonna tell Mr Prescott about it.

677
01:00:31,002 --> 01:00:33,551
Does anybody else
have anything to say?

678
01:00:35,757 --> 01:00:38,510
Hi. Sorry, I'm late.

679
01:00:38,593 --> 01:00:40,766
Sorry. Hi, everybody.

680
01:00:41,471 --> 01:00:43,769
Casual attire today, Whitfield?

681
01:00:46,101 --> 01:00:47,853
Yeah, trousers, yeah.

682
01:00:47,978 --> 01:00:50,982
New product line.
Testing 'em out. Pretty good.

683
01:00:51,064 --> 01:00:53,567
- Good fabric.
- Good idea.

684
01:00:54,109 --> 01:00:56,783
- Christy, you have something to say.
- Yes.

685
01:00:56,862 --> 01:00:59,832
I came up with some more cuts
in the Middle States area.

686
01:00:59,906 --> 01:01:01,749
Let me pass these out.

687
01:01:01,825 --> 01:01:05,204
Why can't you be
more like her, Davis?

688
01:01:06,371 --> 01:01:09,250
Mr Prescott!
Well, what a surprise!

689
01:01:10,417 --> 01:01:13,758
Art, I haven't received
the full report on the cutbacks yet...

690
01:01:13,759 --> 01:01:16,347
<i>so</i> I thought I'd drop in
and see what the problem is.

691
01:01:16,464 --> 01:01:19,388
No problem.
No, sir. Everything is tip-top.

692
01:01:19,467 --> 01:01:21,765
Whitfield has pointed out
a few wrinkles...

693
01:01:21,845 --> 01:01:24,769
and we are going
to iron those wrinkles out.

694
01:01:25,807 --> 01:01:27,901
You don't mind
if I stay for a few minutes, do you?

695
01:01:27,976 --> 01:01:29,728
Yes, sir.

696
01:01:30,270 --> 01:01:33,365
- Which one of you is Whitfield?
- Oh, my God!

697
01:01:33,440 --> 01:01:36,364
Nosebleed! Dry heat!
Get 'em all the time!

698
01:01:36,443 --> 01:01:39,242
Oh, God!
No sight for the squeamish.

699
01:01:40,572 --> 01:01:42,281
<i>Who was that?</i>

700
01:01:42,282 --> 01:01:44,580
Well, that's the new boy, Whitfield.

701
01:01:53,585 --> 01:01:54,837
Sorry.

702
01:01:55,545 --> 01:01:57,343
Needed some supplies.

703
01:01:57,422 --> 01:01:59,720
Well, back to business.

704
01:02:00,800 --> 01:02:03,428
A few of these, and...

705
01:02:03,511 --> 01:02:05,184
Oh, God!

706
01:02:06,056 --> 01:02:08,605
You're from Receiving,
aren't you?

707
01:02:09,517 --> 01:02:11,645
<i>Isee you're a workaholic.</i>

708
01:02:15,440 --> 01:02:17,158
Yeah, well...

709
01:02:18,818 --> 01:02:20,946
I got a lot of work to do.

710
01:02:22,864 --> 01:02:26,994
- What are you doing here so late?
- I'm a workaholic too.

711
01:02:27,494 --> 01:02:29,997
Wow. You mean we have
something in common?

712
01:02:32,707 --> 01:02:36,883
So, what's all this supposed to be?

713
01:02:36,962 --> 01:02:41,386
It's the heart and soul of an idea
you hated: Expansion in the Midwest.

714
01:02:41,387 --> 01:02:43,681
I don't hate it.
I just think it's risky.

715
01:02:43,843 --> 01:02:45,811
Furthermore,
Mr Prescott doesn't want it.

716
01:02:45,887 --> 01:02:48,265
It's a waste of time to pursue it.

717
01:02:49,224 --> 01:02:51,943
But if something's right,
how can it be a waste of time?

718
01:02:52,018 --> 01:02:55,272
There is no right or wrong.
There is only opinion.

719
01:02:57,941 --> 01:03:01,866
You know, in <i>some</i> states,
you can get arrested for saying that.

720
01:03:03,697 --> 01:03:06,120
All right. Convince me.

721
01:03:06,866 --> 01:03:09,745
Convince me then that
your opinion is the right one.

722
01:03:11,037 --> 01:03:12,539
All right.

723
01:03:13,081 --> 01:03:16,210
Take a look at this. And this.

724
01:03:16,876 --> 01:03:19,504
<i>And, yeah.</i>

725
01:03:19,629 --> 01:03:21,927
<i>Peruse that.</i>

726
01:03:22,007 --> 01:03:25,261
Why do you keep saying
the exact opposite of what I say?

727
01:03:25,262 --> 01:03:29,106
- 'Cause you keep saying stupid things.
- Will you look at these figures?

728
01:03:29,180 --> 01:03:31,353
They prove that
the elimination of salaries...

729
01:03:31,433 --> 01:03:34,114
would create a war chest for
the defence of the Pemrose Corporation.

730
01:03:34,185 --> 01:03:36,346
- Can't you see that?
- No, I can't. I'll tell you why.

731
01:03:36,354 --> 01:03:39,483
Closing those factories is just gonna
send a panic through the market.

732
01:03:39,566 --> 01:03:43,070
- That might happen or that might not.
- No, it will happen.

733
01:03:43,194 --> 01:03:46,915
All right, close the centres,
put thousands of people out of work.

734
01:03:46,990 --> 01:03:49,834
You're gonna <i>waste</i> all your profits
on unemployment contributions...

735
01:03:49,909 --> 01:03:52,537
severance pay, union lawsuits.

736
01:03:53,371 --> 01:03:55,044
Are you all right?

737
01:03:55,123 --> 01:03:57,922
- My blood sugar's dropping.
- What?

738
01:03:58,001 --> 01:04:00,424
It's just my mind wandered in
the middle of what you were saying.

739
01:04:00,503 --> 01:04:04,224
It means I need food.
Do you <i>wanna</i> get a bite?

740
01:04:04,299 --> 01:04:08,270
- Yeah, come on. I'll buy you dinner.
- No, no, no. Dutch.

741
01:04:10,847 --> 01:04:14,067
Just tell me one more time
what your solution is to this crisis.

742
01:04:14,142 --> 01:04:18,022
- We don't cut. We expand.
- I agree.

743
01:04:18,104 --> 01:04:21,449
Expansion is a positive reaction
to the universe.

744
01:04:21,524 --> 01:04:24,198
While retraction
or cutting back or pulling off...

745
01:04:24,277 --> 01:04:26,951
Those are all negative forces.

746
01:04:27,030 --> 01:04:31,126
I used to be very negative, and
then I took this personality workshop.

747
01:04:31,534 --> 01:04:33,502
My whole life turned around.

748
01:04:34,287 --> 01:04:36,460
Hiya. My name's Sheila.

749
01:04:37,040 --> 01:04:40,544
You make a good-lookin' couple.
How long you been goin' together?

750
01:04:40,627 --> 01:04:44,302
- About 20 minutes.
- First <i>date,</i> huh? Good luck.

751
01:04:44,381 --> 01:04:46,383
No, we're business colleagues.

752
01:04:46,466 --> 01:04:48,764
Colleagues! Who needs that?

753
01:04:48,843 --> 01:04:51,062
You should go together.
You look good together.

754
01:04:55,475 --> 01:04:57,318
Did you wanna order?

755
01:04:58,269 --> 01:05:02,069
- Yeah, we need to see some menus.
- Menus! I'm sorry.

756
01:05:03,149 --> 01:05:06,653
I'm studying to be an actress. I'm
a better actress than I am a waitress.

757
01:05:06,736 --> 01:05:09,660
Concentration, that's my big problem.
I'll be right back.

758
01:05:12,158 --> 01:05:14,204
Well, Sheila's in favour
of expansion.

759
01:05:14,205 --> 01:05:18,503
We should bring her to our next meeting.
Art Thomas would like her a lot.

760
01:05:18,873 --> 01:05:21,501
Sheila is also in favour of us
seeing each other.

761
01:05:21,584 --> 01:05:24,963
- Yes, well, Sheila is clearly a nut.
- I heard that.

762
01:05:25,046 --> 01:05:27,344
You should try to be
more positive with your life...

763
01:05:27,465 --> 01:05:29,809
or you're gonna wind up miserable.

764
01:05:29,884 --> 01:05:31,386
She heard me.

765
01:05:35,056 --> 01:05:38,517
I'm having a nice time.
How 'bout you?

766
01:05:38,518 --> 01:05:40,612
Yes, very nice.

767
01:05:40,687 --> 01:05:42,610
Well, it's pleasant walking.

768
01:05:42,689 --> 01:05:45,283
I <i>mean,</i>
I don't want to imply anything.

769
01:05:47,152 --> 01:05:51,032
About your expansion plan,
I did some checking...

770
01:05:51,114 --> 01:05:55,961
and we can get some tax breaks if we
put up a facility in the Midwest region.

771
01:05:56,703 --> 01:05:59,172
You checked? Earlier today?

772
01:05:59,247 --> 01:06:00,874
That's great.

773
01:06:00,957 --> 01:06:03,631
The powers that be seem
to want the cutting, but I...

774
01:06:03,710 --> 01:06:08,261
I've been trying to stay open
to your ideas... your business ideas.

775
01:06:08,381 --> 01:06:10,054
That's great.

776
01:06:16,347 --> 01:06:19,066
Okay, so you're
open to my business ideas.

777
01:06:19,142 --> 01:06:22,227
Now, how about
my after-work ideas?

778
01:06:22,228 --> 01:06:25,983
Don't push. Yesterday,
I thought you were obnoxious.

779
01:06:29,194 --> 01:06:31,743
You know, a lot of people
start out that way.

780
01:06:33,239 --> 01:06:36,334
- They usually end up gettin' married.
- Don't hold your breath.

781
01:06:36,409 --> 01:06:38,127
Come on.

782
01:06:39,871 --> 01:06:43,125
<i>Look,</i> I think
you're secretly crazy about me.

783
01:06:43,208 --> 01:06:46,508
And I think you'd feel a lot better
if you'd just admit it.

784
01:06:47,545 --> 01:06:51,300
Come on. You'll like me.
I'm an acquired taste.

785
01:07:08,066 --> 01:07:11,286
My dad insisted
on buying me this.

786
01:07:13,196 --> 01:07:15,244
A round-trip ticket
back to Kansas.

787
01:07:17,116 --> 01:07:19,118
I almost traded it in
a couple of times.

788
01:07:20,203 --> 01:07:22,001
But now, it's kind of a symbol.

789
01:07:22,121 --> 01:07:24,340
The day I use this ticket...

790
01:07:25,041 --> 01:07:27,043
is the day New York
has beaten me.

791
01:07:29,087 --> 01:07:31,089
You know,
I just noticed something.

792
01:07:31,631 --> 01:07:35,511
- You're kind of a mess.
- Thank you.

793
01:07:35,593 --> 01:07:38,767
- Did anybody ever tell you that?
- You're the first.

794
01:07:38,846 --> 01:07:41,190
So what I was wonderin' was...

795
01:07:43,351 --> 01:07:46,562
how you can be
<i>so</i> incredibly beautiful...

796
01:07:46,563 --> 01:07:48,691
and be such a mess?

797
01:07:51,442 --> 01:07:53,945
When two people get involved
on a project together...

798
01:07:54,028 --> 01:07:57,373
there's a danger
of getting emotionally involved.

799
01:07:58,783 --> 01:08:00,626
That would be bad.

800
01:08:00,702 --> 01:08:04,047
They confuse the intensity
of their involvement on the project...

801
01:08:04,122 --> 01:08:06,375
and mistake it
<i>as a</i> relationship.

802
01:08:08,710 --> 01:08:13,130
- What are you, a shrink?
- It's happened to me.

803
01:08:13,131 --> 01:08:15,429
It's actually still happening
to me, I guess.

804
01:08:15,508 --> 01:08:17,806
And then...

805
01:08:17,885 --> 01:08:21,355
the project ends and they find
they don't have anything to talk about.

806
01:08:22,849 --> 01:08:25,523
Okay, it's settled then.

807
01:08:27,520 --> 01:08:30,945
We won't get involved
while we're working on this project.

808
01:08:33,026 --> 01:08:34,573
Right.

809
01:08:42,285 --> 01:08:44,504
<i>So who is he?</i>

810
01:08:44,579 --> 01:08:45,956
Who?

811
01:08:46,039 --> 01:08:48,963
Who? My competition.

812
01:08:49,042 --> 01:08:50,715
Just a guy.

813
01:08:51,836 --> 01:08:54,055
All right,
<i>so</i> why don't we call this guy?

814
01:08:54,130 --> 01:08:56,132
Tell him you met a new guy.
The whole thing is off.

815
01:08:56,215 --> 01:08:59,970
- I can't call him.
- Why not?

816
01:09:00,053 --> 01:09:02,431
His wife might answer
the phone.

817
01:09:04,932 --> 01:09:07,560
- Big mistake.
- Yeah, well, let's not talk about it.

818
01:09:07,644 --> 01:09:10,614
- I've done a lot of stupid things...
- I bet you have.

819
01:09:10,688 --> 01:09:12,440
- But I have never...
- Ever?

820
01:09:15,109 --> 01:09:17,612
Been involved with a married man.

821
01:09:18,071 --> 01:09:20,745
Well, he was sort of separated
when we started.

822
01:09:23,868 --> 01:09:26,291
Yeah, <i>well,</i>
it turned out to be a lie.

823
01:09:26,371 --> 01:09:28,965
The whole thing was a mistake.

824
01:09:30,083 --> 01:09:32,927
But we live and we learn
and we move on...

825
01:09:47,517 --> 01:09:49,144
That wasn't bad.

826
01:09:50,311 --> 01:09:51,733
Thank you.

827
01:09:54,065 --> 01:09:56,488
Can you do it again
just as good?

828
01:09:59,278 --> 01:10:01,246
I could try.

829
01:11:11,517 --> 01:11:14,361
- Where were you all weekend?
- At least begin with "good morning."

830
01:11:14,437 --> 01:11:16,940
I'm madder than hell!

831
01:11:17,982 --> 01:11:20,576
I want to know why
you weren't answering your phone.

832
01:11:20,651 --> 01:11:22,619
I owe a lot to you, Howard.

833
01:11:22,695 --> 01:11:25,073
I'll always be grateful for the chance
you gave me in this company...

834
01:11:25,239 --> 01:11:26,991
and the things I've learned.

835
01:11:27,533 --> 01:11:30,787
What is this?
What are you leading up to?

836
01:11:30,870 --> 01:11:32,668
<i>I wanna work with you.</i>

837
01:11:32,747 --> 01:11:35,546
<i>Irespect you
more than you know, but...</i>

838
01:11:36,459 --> 01:11:40,180
I can't be involved with you
outside the office any more.

839
01:11:42,423 --> 01:11:44,175
Hello?

840
01:11:50,473 --> 01:11:55,229
Yes, I'm looking for the transportation
<i>costs</i> from Toledo dating September...

841
01:11:55,311 --> 01:11:57,109
I'll call you back.

842
01:12:00,483 --> 01:12:03,453
<i>Look,</i> I'm not
gonna pressure you on this.

843
01:12:03,528 --> 01:12:05,405
I want you to take your own time...

844
01:12:06,239 --> 01:12:08,617
and decide what's best for you.

845
01:12:08,741 --> 01:12:10,459
Thank you.

846
01:12:12,703 --> 01:12:15,707
I do think the timing's
a little ironic, though.

847
01:12:16,666 --> 01:12:18,714
I was gonna tell you
last night...

848
01:12:19,585 --> 01:12:22,930
that Vera and I have agreed
on terms for a divorce.

849
01:12:24,715 --> 01:12:28,436
I only wish that Vera and I
could have worked things out sooner.

850
01:12:29,095 --> 01:12:32,065
That way, you and I
might have had a chance.

851
01:12:34,308 --> 01:12:37,278
This arrived this morning
by messenger.

852
01:12:38,437 --> 01:12:40,940
Davenport has called
an emergency meeting...

853
01:12:41,023 --> 01:12:44,698
of the board of directors
for Monday morning...

854
01:12:44,819 --> 01:12:47,242
and he's offering
to take over the company.

855
01:12:48,948 --> 01:12:52,998
I'm inviting all key personnel to spend
the weekend at my house in Litchfield.

856
01:12:53,828 --> 01:12:55,671
I'd like you to be there too.

857
01:12:56,956 --> 01:12:58,958
Of course I'll be there.

858
01:13:01,252 --> 01:13:04,677
One more question... personal.

859
01:13:05,047 --> 01:13:09,018
Just out of curiosity,
who were you with last night?

860
01:13:10,720 --> 01:13:13,644
Whitfield. Carlton Whitfield.

861
01:13:14,974 --> 01:13:18,444
It was all business.
Some of his ideas are brilliant.

862
01:13:18,519 --> 01:13:21,944
I'm looking forward to hearing 'em.
I have to talk to him today.

863
01:13:23,733 --> 01:13:28,034
Those notes that I took from Whitfield's
office... I'd like them back, please.

864
01:13:28,112 --> 01:13:30,956
Of course.
I'll get them to you.

865
01:13:31,032 --> 01:13:33,205
Heads up. Thanks.

866
01:13:35,745 --> 01:13:39,039
What's your hurry?
What's goin' on?

867
01:13:39,040 --> 01:13:41,418
I got a special delivery
here marked "urgent."

868
01:13:41,542 --> 01:13:43,260
I'm watching you, Foster.

869
01:13:43,336 --> 01:13:45,134
Just remember, every minute...

870
01:13:45,212 --> 01:13:47,180
God is watching you.

871
01:13:48,925 --> 01:13:52,429
Excuse me, Miss, I'm a reporter for the
Times, and I couldn't help noticing...

872
01:13:52,511 --> 01:13:54,672
you look like <i>a woman</i>
Who's recently been made love to.

873
01:13:54,680 --> 01:13:56,978
- Not here.
- You weren't made love to here.

874
01:13:57,058 --> 01:13:59,607
Was it anywhere within the New York
State lines, because we usually let...

875
01:13:59,685 --> 01:14:02,609
<i>the philadelphia Gazette
handle Pennsylvania.</i>

876
01:14:04,815 --> 01:14:06,909
What's up?
You seem kind of upset.

877
01:14:06,984 --> 01:14:09,078
I hate men.

878
01:14:09,153 --> 01:14:11,406
Well, I'm glad
I'm not one of'em.

879
01:14:13,282 --> 01:14:15,376
Listen, there's something
I gotta explain to you.

880
01:14:15,451 --> 01:14:19,206
I have something to tell you too.
I did something I wish I hadn't, and...

881
01:14:19,207 --> 01:14:20,707
All right, look.

882
01:14:22,208 --> 01:14:24,677
- This weekend?
- Can't.

883
01:14:24,752 --> 01:14:29,053
- I <i>have some loose ends to tie up.</i>
- Good!

884
01:14:29,256 --> 01:14:32,385
- I'll take care of it.
- Have a nice weekend. See you Monday.

885
01:14:37,765 --> 01:14:39,813
Excuse me, Miss.
I'm sorry. Excuse me!

886
01:14:41,477 --> 01:14:43,479
You didn't see me.
I wasn't here.

887
01:14:47,316 --> 01:14:50,240
- Where is he? Where'd he go?
- I didn't see him. He wasn't here.

888
01:14:59,996 --> 01:15:01,919
You still here?

889
01:15:02,915 --> 01:15:04,588
You look great.

890
01:15:08,379 --> 01:15:10,757
The end of the second lap,
you still got a comfortable lead.

891
01:15:15,970 --> 01:15:17,847
Excuse me again.

892
01:15:20,683 --> 01:15:22,310
- Hi, boss.
- Shit!

893
01:15:25,396 --> 01:15:26,943
Bye, boss.

894
01:15:30,151 --> 01:15:32,028
- Hi.
- What are you doing here?

895
01:15:32,111 --> 01:15:34,079
Looking for Whitfield.
Got a delivery for him.

896
01:15:34,155 --> 01:15:35,782
Why are you wearing a suit?

897
01:15:37,491 --> 01:15:40,586
- Because of the funeral.
- Whose funeral?

898
01:15:40,661 --> 01:15:44,131
A friend. He died.
We buried him.

899
01:15:45,166 --> 01:15:47,009
What is all this stuff?

900
01:15:47,960 --> 01:15:52,056
Production performance charts
for the Midwest region, I guess.

901
01:15:55,176 --> 01:15:56,644
Where is Whitfield?

902
01:15:57,970 --> 01:15:59,472
He's not here?

903
01:16:00,014 --> 01:16:03,516
- Have you ever seen Whitfield?
- Yes, sir.

904
01:16:03,517 --> 01:16:05,144
Well, lots of times.

905
01:16:05,311 --> 01:16:07,860
I deliver here every day.
Great guy.

906
01:16:08,814 --> 01:16:10,862
How does he get
all this information?

907
01:16:10,941 --> 01:16:14,286
Well, it's available in most
quarterly stock reports...

908
01:16:15,529 --> 01:16:17,202
probably.

909
01:16:19,742 --> 01:16:21,836
- Take this up to my office.
- Yes, sir.

910
01:16:27,875 --> 01:16:31,095
- You're not comin'?
- L'II be there in a minute.

911
01:16:42,681 --> 01:16:44,854
One question:
What the hell are you doin'?

912
01:16:44,934 --> 01:16:47,437
- Having a nervous breakdown.
- No wonder.

913
01:16:47,520 --> 01:16:50,400
<i>Look,</i> nothin' good can come from this.
If you get caught, you get canned.

914
01:16:50,439 --> 01:16:52,720
If you don't get caught, you become
one of them... a suit.

915
01:16:52,733 --> 01:16:57,159
- It's a no-win situation.
- I'm still a half a step ahead of them.

916
01:17:08,415 --> 01:17:12,710
<i>I hear music when I look at you.</i>

917
01:17:12,711 --> 01:17:15,931
Aunt Vera, hi. How are you?

918
01:17:18,008 --> 01:17:21,057
<i>I'm in the mood for love.</i>

919
01:17:21,137 --> 01:17:24,983
<i>Simply because you're near me.</i>

920
01:17:25,057 --> 01:17:27,981
A medley. Gee, that's nice.

921
01:17:28,060 --> 01:17:30,108
Why are you singing a medley?

922
01:17:30,187 --> 01:17:34,112
<i>I get no kick from champagne.</i>

923
01:17:34,191 --> 01:17:40,039
- <i>Mere alcohol doesn't thrill me at all</i>
- <i>Please, don't sing any more.</i>

924
01:17:41,407 --> 01:17:42,659
Oh, God!

925
01:17:42,783 --> 01:17:45,536
I haven't sung in years.
You see what you do to me?

926
01:17:45,619 --> 01:17:47,292
He's on his way up.

927
01:17:47,371 --> 01:17:50,966
